<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1778,2036]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,419,1778,1804]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Horn" authorityYear="1868" box="[430,657,1779,1804]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Triarthron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lecontei">
<emphasis box="[430,657,1779,1804]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Triarthron lecontei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly variable, both within and between populations, in the following characters: strigulate microsculpture of head and pronotum (dense to absent); punctation of head and pronotum; elytra (glabrous to densely setose); lateral pronotal margins (rounded to angulate); outer margin of male metatibia (angulate or not); dentition of dorsal lamina of posterior margin of male metafemur (3–6 teeth); and shape of large tooth-like lamina at apex of male metafemur. These non-genital characters do not consistently vary in concert with one another. However, the characters of the aedeagus are consistent throughout the species range.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310890" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5310890" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310890/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" startId="10.[151,269,1289,1313]" targetBox="[237,1354,203,1256]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1289,1381]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,335,1289,1313]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">FIGURES 8–13.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[341,551,1289,1312]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Horn" authorityYear="1868" box="[341,547,1289,1312]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Triarthron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lecontei">Triarthron lecontei</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
8. Right antenna, dorsal view. 9. Mandibles, dorsal view. 10. Male right metafemur and metatibia. 11. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 12. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 13. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 11, 13), 0.5 mm (Figs. 8, 9, 12), 0.75 mm (Fig. 10).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1428,1841]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
We have not found characters to separate this species from Palearctic 
<taxonomicName authority="Markel" authorityName="Markel" authorityYear="1840" box="[1079,1321,1428,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Triarthron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maerkelii">
<emphasis box="[1079,1093,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">T</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1113,1224,1428,1453]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">maerkelii</emphasis>
Märkel
</taxonomicName>
with the description and figures presented in 
<bibRefCitation author="Daffner, H." box="[581,758,1466,1492]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="9 - 163" refId="ref29545" refString="Daffner, H. (1983) Revision der palaarktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 44, 9 - 163." type="journal article" year="1983">Daffner (1983)</bibRefCitation>
but have not seen enough specimens to be confident that 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Horn" authorityYear="1868" box="[151,273,1505,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Triarthron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lecontei">
<emphasis box="[151,273,1505,1530]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">T. lecontei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1428,1841]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,1544,1570]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species occurs in the north-central parts of western and eastern North America, and seems to be absent from the forested center of the northern part of the continent (
<figureCitation box="[1153,1245,1583,1609]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="11.[151,255,1453,1477]" captionTargetBox="[233,1355,509,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-314@11.[229,1358,506,1426]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 14. Known North American localities of Triarthron lecontei (black dots). In this and all following maps, small white circles indicate major cities." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310892" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310892/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). We have seen specimens from 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[355,465,1621,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<collectingCountry box="[355,460,1621,1647]" name="Canada" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Canada</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[683,894,1621,1647]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[956,1053,1621,1647]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Ontario</collectingRegion>
; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1067,1138,1621,1647]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<collectingCountry box="[1067,1132,1621,1647]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">USA</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[1304,1431,1621,1647]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[151,323,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Massachusetts" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Massachusetts</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[335,442,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Montana</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[453,648,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="New Hampshire" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">New Hampshire</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[659,750,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Oregon</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[762,921,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Pennsylvania" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Pennsylvania</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[933,1031,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Virginia" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Virginia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1043,1185,1660,1686]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Washington</collectingRegion>
